<big><b>Phrasal Verbs (A–F)</b></big>

<big><b>WHAT ARE PHRASAL VERBS?</b></big>

Phrasal verbs are combinations of a verb and one or more particles (prepositions or adverbs).

The meaning of a phrasal verb is often different from the meaning of the individual words.

Examples:

• Break down = explain
• Give up = stop trying
• Look after = take care of

Phrasal verbs are very common in everyday English.


<big><b>Phrasal Verbs Starting with A</b></big>

<b>Act on</b> : take action because of something

Example:
• The company acted on the customer's complaint.

<b>Act out</b> : express feelings through actions

Example:
• The child acted out his favorite movie scene.

<b>Add up</b> : make sense

Example:
• His explanation does not add up.

<b>Ask around</b> : ask many people for information

Example:
• I asked around to find a good teacher.

<b>Ask out</b> : invite someone on a date

Example:
• He asked her out for dinner.


<big><b>Phrasal Verbs Starting with B</b></big>

<b>Back away</b> : move backwards from something

Example:
• The dog barked and I backed away.

<b>Back down</b> : stop defending a position

Example:
• She refused to back down during the discussion.

<b>Back up</b> : support; make a copy

Example:
• Always back up your important files.

<b>Break down</b> : explain; stop working

Example:
• Can you break down the problem for me?

<b>Break into</b> : enter by force

Example:
• Someone broke into the house last night.

<b>Break out</b> : start suddenly

Example:
• A fire broke out in the building.

<b>Break up</b> : separate; end a relationship

Example:
• They decided to break up.


<big><b>Phrasal Verbs Starting with C</b></big>

<b>Call back</b> : return a phone call

Example:
• I will call you back later.

<b>Call off</b> : cancel

Example:
• They called off the meeting.

<b>Carry on</b> : continue

Example:
• Please carry on with your work.

<b>Carry out</b> : perform or complete

Example:
• The scientists carried out an experiment.

<b>Catch up</b> : reach the same level

Example:
• I need to catch up with my classmates.

<b>Check in</b> : register at a hotel or airport

Example:
• We checked in two hours before the flight.

<b>Come across</b> : find by chance

Example:
• I came across an old photograph.

<b>Come up with</b> : think of an idea

Example:
• She came up with a brilliant solution.

<b>Count on</b> : depend on

Example:
• You can count on me.


<big><b>Phrasal Verbs Starting with D</b></big>

<b>Deal with</b> : handle a situation

Example:
• She knows how to deal with problems.

<b>Do over</b> : do again

Example:
• The teacher asked us to do the exercise over.

<b>Do without</b> : manage without something

Example:
• We can do without unnecessary expenses.

<b>Dress up</b> : wear formal clothes

Example:
• Everyone dressed up for the celebration.

<b>Drop off</b> : deliver; fall asleep

Example:
• Can you drop me off at the station?


<big><b>Phrasal Verbs Starting with E</b></big>

<b>Eat out</b> : eat in a restaurant

Example:
• We usually eat out on weekends.

<b>End up</b> : finally reach a result

Example:
• He ended up becoming a doctor.


<big><b>Phrasal Verbs Starting with F</b></big>

<b>Fall apart</b> : break into pieces

Example:
• The old chair fell apart.

<b>Fall behind</b> : fail to keep up

Example:
• He fell behind in his studies.

<b>Fall for</b> : be deceived by; fall in love

Example:
• Don't fall for that trick.

<b>Figure out</b> : understand or solve

Example:
• I finally figured out the answer.

<b>Fill in</b> : complete information

Example:
• Please fill in the form.

<b>Fill out</b> : complete a form

Example:
• She filled out the application.

<b>Find out</b> : discover

Example:
• We found out the truth.

<b>Focus on</b> : concentrate on

Example:
• You should focus on your goals.


<big><b>Tips for Learning Phrasal Verbs</b></big>

• Learn phrasal verbs in context.
• Read example sentences.
• Practice using them in conversations.
• Keep a notebook of new phrasal verbs.
• Review them regularly.


